                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d268">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.3421/45: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-02-13T14:00:00-03:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 13, 1919, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received 4.50 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Embassy’s January 8, 2 p.m. Da Gama<note n="15" xml:id="d268fn15">Brazilian
                        Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> informs me that Brazilian law would
                    support a proposition from an Anglo-American group covering matters contained in
                    Vickers Armstrong proposal forwarded in Embassy’s despatch number 1324 of July
                    22nd, 1918. Government would prefer joint participation rather than a monopoly
                    by a single nation. This matter should be given immediate attention to prevent
                    Vickers Armstrong from pushing their proposal through.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morgan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
